{
  "texts": [
    "Terms Priority map, salience map, conspicuity map, dimensional map, overall (salience or priority) map The primate visual system is organized topographically with multiple retinotopic maps in cortical and subcortical structures.",
    "Because visual spatial attention is manifest in and through such a visual system, it is natural to employ the concept of a map or a set of hierarchical maps in explanations of how attention is allocated.",
    "We suggest that priority map should be used as the most generic, theoretically neutral description of a single map or, alternatively, a map at the top of the hierarchy that serves to prioritize some visual information over other.",
    "It should replace terms such as activation map that has been used in the context of Guided Search (Wolfe, 1994) or master map of locations that has been used in the context of Feature-Integration Theory (Treisman & Souther, 1985).",
    "Salience map should be reserved for maps that index exclusively the feedforward, bottom-up, retinal-based, stimulus-driven representation of visual distinctiveness of a feature, stimulus, or location (i.e., salience → Features)."
  ]
}